If you want to go back to a previous activity, no need to

    startActivity(moveView);
    finish();

in your `onBackPressed()`. what you are doing there is starting another instance of that activity and sending the data you want to send back.

Instead do `startActivityForResult()` in your `ViewData.class` and in your `onBackPressed()` in `MainActivity`

    public void onBackPressed() {
        Intent moveView = getIntent();
        //Here your can add whatever values you want to send back to your activity
        moveView.putExtra(&quot;some_key&quot;,value)
        setResult(Activity.RESULT_OK,moveView);
        finish();
    }
then in your `ViewData.class` override `onActivityResult()` there is where you will retrieve the data sent by the current activity. See [Getting a Result from an Activity][1]
The issue you are having with Firestore is that you haven&#39;t initialized with a proper path, maybe due to that you are starting a new instance of `ViewData.class`


  [1]: https://developer.android.com/training/basics/intents/result

NullPointerException: Provided document path must not be null

above error is caused by this line:

    documentID = getIntent().getStringExtra(&quot;documentID&quot;);

here documentID is null.

And to get back into previous activity just remove onBackPressed method or override it as:

    @Override
    public void onBackPressed() {
        super.onBackPressed();
    }

And in your current activity&#39;s onCreate() add this line to make navigation back icon work -

    getSupportActionBar().setDisplayHomeAsUpEnabled(true);

